      "source": [
        "**Multi-View Visual Geolocation**\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "Dual-Task US State Classification & GPS Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "This project implements a sophisticated computer vision pipeline to solve the challenge of visual geolocation. Given four 256×256 images (North, East, South, West) for a single location, the system is engineered to extract environmental cues—such as vegetation, architecture, and road textures—to predict both the US State (Classification) and Precise GPS Coordinates (Regression).\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "I. Technical Architecture: Multi-View Fusion\n",
        "\n",
        "* The core of the solution lies in a Hybrid Transformer-Encoder Architecture. Rather than treating the four directions as independent images, the model processes them as a unified panoramic context.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Backbone Encoders: The pipeline supports both DINOv3 (ViT-L/16) and ConvNeXt V2-Large. These backbones are pre-trained on massive datasets (like LVD-142M) to recognize complex visual patterns across diverse terrains.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Transformer Fusion: A 2-layer Transformer Encoder acts as the \"brain\" of the model. It uses self-attention to correlate features across the four views, allowing the model to understand that a building in the North view and a specific tree species in the West view together signify a particular region.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Dual-Head Output: The fused global descriptor is branched into two specialized MLP heads:\n",
        "\n",
        "* State Head: Outputs logits for 33–50 state indices.\n",
        "\n",
        "* GPS Head: Regresses to normalized latitude and longitude coordinates.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "II. Optimization and Loss Functions\n",
        "\n",
        "* To excel in the competition's specific scoring metric (70% Classification / 30% GPS), the training process utilizes specialized mathematical constraints:\n",
        "\n",
        "* Haversine Distance Loss: For GPS regression, the model is not trained on simple Euclidean distance. Instead, it uses the Haversine Formula, which accounts for the Earth's curvature, ensuring that the model minimizes the actual kilometer-distance error.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Differential Learning Rates: To prevent \"forgetting\" the powerful features learned during pre-training, the backbone is tuned with a very low learning rate (1×10\n",
        "−5\n",
        " ), while the fusion and prediction heads are trained aggressively (2×10\n",
        "−4\n",
        " ).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "III. Post-Processing & Strategic Refinement\n",
        "\n",
        "* The final output is refined through three distinct \"Grandmaster\" strategies to squeeze out maximum accuracy:\n",
        "\n",
        "* 5-Crop Test-Time Augmentation (TTA): The model evaluates multiple versions of the test images (including horizontal flips) and averages the results to reduce prediction variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Ensemble Blending: By combining the high-accuracy classification of the DINOv3 model with the spatial stability of the ConvNeXt model (70/30 weight), the system achieves a more robust final prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "* Hard Grid Snapping: Recognizing that data points are constrained to road networks, the code uses Nearest Neighbor (KNN) search. It identifies the most likely road point in the training database for a given prediction and \"snaps\" the predicted GPS to that coordinate, effectively eliminating impossible \"off-road\" predictions."
      ]
    },
